04101nam a22005535i 9780773554245DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735542457 a10.1515/97807735542452doi  a(DE-B1597)656137  a(OCoLC)1035220287  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aREL1080202bisacsh1 aCianca, Jenn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSacred Ritual, Profane Space :bThe Roman House as Early Christian Meeting Place /cJenn Cianca. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource :b7 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Christianity and Judaism ;v100tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Context of House-Church Christianity -- tRoman Domestic Space -- tRoman Domestic Worship -- tHouse-Church Christianity and Roman Domestic Worship -- tPlacing Ritual: Christians in the Roman House -- tSacred Space and the House Church -- tTowards a Theory of Sacred Space in House-Church Christianity -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first three centuries of Christianity are increasingly seen in modern scholarship as sites of complexity. Sacred Ritual, Profane Space examines the Christian meeting places of the time and overturns long-held notions about the earliest Christians as utopian rather than place-bound people. By mapping what is known from early Christian texts onto the archaeological data for Roman domestic spaces, Jenn Cianca provides a new lens for examining the relationship between early Christianity and sites of worship. She proposes that not only were Roman homes sacred sites in their own right but they were also considered sacred by the Christian communities that used them. In many cases, meeting space would have included the presence of the Roman domestic cult shrines. Despite the fact that the domestic cult was polytheistic, Cianca asserts that its practices likely continued in places used for worship by Christians. She also argues that continued practice of the domestic cult in Roman domestic spaces did not preclude Christians from using houses as churches or from understanding their rituals or their meeting places as sacred. Raising a host of questions about identity, ritual affiliation, and domestic practice, Sacred Ritual, Profane Space demonstrates how sacred space was constructed through ritual enactment in early Christian communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristianityzRome. 0aDomestic spacezRome. 0aHouse churcheszRome. 0aRites and ceremonieszRome. 0aSacred spacezRome. 7aRELIGION / Christian Church / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773554245?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773554245423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773554245/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles